</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-66_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-67_ pf-text-1"><strong>Choking </strong>- Young children are particularly at risk of choking. Effective first aid can save lives in such emergencies.





































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-69_ pf-text-1"><strong>Allergies </strong>- With the rise in childhood allergies, promptly recognising and treating allergic reactions is a critical skill.





































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-71_ pf-text-1"><strong>Injury prevention</strong> - Training should also cover preventive measures to reduce injuries in early years settings.






































